  "prompt": "Which is the correct past tense of override, overrode or overrided?",
  "response": "The correct past tense of \"override\" is \"overrode.\" \"Overrided\" is not a standard form in English. Here's how it conjugates:\n\n- Present: override\n- Past: overrode\n- Past Participle: overridden\n\nFor example, you might say, \"The new policy overrode the old one,\" or \"The settings have been overridden by the administrator.\"",
